So the universe is currently ~14 billion years old.  Our galaxy has
been forging new stars continuously for most of that period, but the
current estimate is that there's only enough interstellar gas left for
another ~~10 billion years of star formation.  Let's be conservative
and double that.  This is the Stelliferous Era: the first 30-35
billion years of the universe.

Once star formation stops, the stars will start going out -- biggest
and brightest first, then gradually working down the main sequence.
So, ~5 billion years after the end of the Stelliferous Era, there
won't be any F or hotter stars left.  By ~~50 billion years after, the
last yellow dwarf will be winking out.  Call this the Reddening Era.
By the time the universe is ~~100 billion years old, all the bright
stars are gone.  What's left: red and orange dwarves and stellar
remnants.

We now enter onto the long, calm middle age of the universe.  Because
of convection, small stars live /much/ longer than big ones.  The
smallest red dwarves may last several trillion years.  So, the Red
Dwarf Era may last from around 100 billion AD to, let's say, 5
trillion.  In a sense, the first 100 billion years of the universe is
just a bright, energetic prologue, barely a fiftieth as long as the
next chapter.

This is an era in which not much happens, but that's not necessarily
bad.  The universe continues to expand, and distant galaxies and
quasars may gradually wink out of existence for us, but the Milky Way
should be stable over this time scale.  Eventually, dynamic relaxation
will cause most of the Milky Way to disintegrate into interstellar
space, while the rest will get eaten by the black hole at the center,
but that's going to take a few orders of magnitude more --
quadrillions or quintillions of years, not trillions.

This is a universe that's still reasonably hospitable to Life As We
Know It.  Chemical-based life should still be possible.  Red dwarves
aren't bright, but even a little star produces plenty of energy, so
there's plenty of power to support advanced civilizations doing
interesting things.  The Red Dwarf Milky Way could still include
billions of worlds of sunlight -- okay, red sunlight -- breathable
air, and running water, supporting species or cultures that think in
time scales of billions or tens of billions of years.  It could be the
long red afternoon of life in the universe.

Of course, everything comes to an end, and eventually even the dimmest
red dwarf will wink out.

Still... this seems like a potentially interesting setting.  Has
anyone ever done anything with it?

Doug M.
