Two other thoughts occur.

One, it'll be a universe of dark skies.  Every star we see in the sky
is either a giant or, if a dwarf, early K or hotter.  Not a single red
dwarf is naked-eye visible.  Even eyes that see in infrared wouldn't
see red dwarves unless they were quite close -- less than a light year
away.  And the Milky Way itself would be invisible.  Dark skies.

Two, the radioactive elements that heat the interior of Earthlike
planets will have long since been exhausted, and there'll be no
supernovas to forge new ones.  So, planets may exist, but they won't
have volcanoes or plate tectonics.

What else?

