To pick some nits:

(1)  There are plenty of long lived radioisotopes with halflives much
longer than those of the uranium, thorium, and potassium isotopes
that provide the bulk of Earth's heating.  Granted, these will likely
not provide enough heating to drive plate tectonics, at least on
a planet similar to Earth.  However, one can imagine systems where
the heating is provided gravitationally, for example by tidal heating
of a earth-sized moon around a gas giant orbiting close to a small star.

(2) Type-I supernovas will continue long into the future.  These occur
when a white dwarf accretes enough matter to drive it over the
limit at which it collapses.  Such events will continue to occur
as binary star systems that contain one or two such stars
have their orbits decay by emission of gravitational radiation.

(3) The significant isotope potassium-40 is not produced by
the R-process in core implosion supernovas, but by the S-process.
I imagine it would also be produced to some extent in type-I
SNs.

Paul
