True. For an observer in starfield like the disc around Sun, red
dwarfs would be invisible.

But what about a globular cluster? Sun happens to be far from all of
them - the two brightest, Omega Centauri and 47 Tucanae are dim
nebulae. But what would a present day globular cluster look like for
an observer inside? No main sequence stars hotter than G. A scattering
of red giants being the brightest. An even thinner scattering of new
planetary nebulae and Type I supernova remnants.

How numerous, in current globular clusters, are yellow, orange, red
and brown dwarfs? How much of the total mass is taken up by each? How
much of total luminosity?

In older globular clusters, yellow dwarfs would be gone. Red dwarfs
would remain. And remember that  globular clusters evaporate slowly -
the remaining stars would move even closer together. So, the red
dwarfs would be so near that they might still be visible.

Also, there are the core nd bulge of Milky Way, which even now is a
dense concentration of old stars and would get denser yet.

