Consider the upper reaches of the Earth's atmosphere.  That air has
a certain temperature; the molecules in it are moving at a variety
of speeds, with the average determined by the temperature, but there
is no upper limit.
(See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boltzman_distribution )
Some miniscule fraction of those molecules will be travelling at speeds
greater than escape velocity.  Half of them will be travelling in a
direction away from the Earth rather than towards it.  These molecules
will either escape, or collide with another molecule--in which case,
do the whole exercise over again.  The result is a very very slow loss
of gas molecules.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;Mars has lost most air and perhaps some water. Venus has lost all
&gt;water and not much air. How much is Earth losing? Can a habitable
&gt;planet keep air and water for really long timescales?
">

The lighter the gas molecule, the more likely it is to escape.  Earth
probably lost a lot of free hydrogen before it had an oxidizing atmosphere.
Helium is scarce for this reason; every alpha decay that has ever occured
on Earth has produced a helium atom, but none of them stick around very
long once released into the atmosphere.  A water molecule is much lighter
than a molecule of Oxygen, Nitrogen, or Carbon Dioxide.  Plus, if a water
molecule is temporarily broken up--at room temperature, some fraction of
water molecules will be separated into H+ and OH- ions--there is a chance
for the hydrogen atom to escape.  So, water goes away faster than other
gasses we consider air.  The larger the planet's escape velocity, the
harder it is for gasses to escape, and the cooler the planet's atmosphere
the fewer gas molecules will be moving at escape velocity--that is why
Earth has retained more volatiles than Mars and more water than Venus.
However, even in the case of Earth, gasses are constantly being added to
the atmosphere via geological activity, and constantly escapes into space.
The Earth has had more atmosphere at times in the past than it does now.
Dragonflies with 36&quot; wingspans could fly thanks to the greater air denisty,
and three foot long millipedes needed the higher oxygen concentration.

