While that's true for the vast vast majority of solid bodies at that
point in time, there's nothing to say you can't have a &quot;cold start&quot; of
tidal effects very late in the game... it's just less and less likely
over time. As an exmaple, picture a moon in a distant retrograde orbit
around a planet, or a moon in a prograde orbit around a planet close
to the star. Over time those orbits will change, but sloooowly... in
the first case, body tides will walk the moon in towards the parent
planet, while in the second tides induced by the star on the planet
will start to walk the tidally-locked moon back toward the planet. In
either case, that means the moon's period will be changing, and if
that period comes into resonance with a second (or third) moon in the
system, you can evolve a system into an Io-like situation late in
life.

Likely? No, not in the least. But like blue stragglers, anything that
can happen, will, given enough time... and for this setting, the one
thing you have plenty of is time.

